a City, Panama, Programa Centroamericano de Maestría en Entomología, Universidad de Panamá, Panama City, Panama; Li, A.O.Y., School of Biological Sciences, University of Hong Kong, Hong Kong, Hong Kong; Buria, L.M., Laboratorio de Limnología, INIBIOMA, Universidad Nacional Del Comahue-CONICET, Bariloche, Argentina; Villanueva, V.D., Laboratorio de Limnología, INIBIOMA, Universidad Nacional Del Comahue-CONICET, Bariloche, Argentina; Zúñiga, M.C., Centro Para la Investigación en Sistemas Sostenibles de Producción Agropecuaria, CIPAV, Carrera 25 No. 6-62 Cali, Colombia; Pringle, C.M., Odum School of Ecology, University of Georgia, Athens, GA 30602-2602, United States","Most hypotheses explaining the general gradient of higher diversity toward the equator are implicit or explicit about greater species packing in the tropics. However, global patterns of diversity within guilds, including trophic guilds (i.e., groups of organisms that use similar food resources), are poorly known. We explored global diversity patterns of a key trophic guild in stream ecosystems, the detritivore shredders. This was motivated by the fundamental ecological role of shredders as decomposers of leaf litter and by some records pointing to low shredder diversity and abundance in the tropics, which contrasts with diversity patterns of most major taxa for which broad-scale latitudinal patterns haven been examined. Given this evidence, we hypothesized that shredders are more abundant and diverse in temperate than in tropical streams, and that this pattern is related to the higher temperatures and lower availability of high-quality leaf litter in the tropics. Our comprehensive global survey (129 stream sites from 14 regions on six continents) corroborated the expectedlatitudinal pattern and showed that shredder distribution (abundance, diversity and assemblage composition) was explained by a combination of factors, including water temperature (some taxa were restricted to cool waters) and biogeography (some taxa were more diverse in particular biogeographic realms). In contrast to our hypothesis, shredder diversity was unrelated to leaf toughness, but it was inversely related to litter diversity. Our findings markedly contrast with global trends of diversity for most taxa, and with the general rule of higher consumer diversity at higher levels of resource diversity. Moreover, they highlight the emerging role of temperature in understanding global patterns of diversity, which is of great relevance in the face of projected global warming. © 2011 by the Ecological Society of America.","Global distribution pattern; Latitudinal diversity gradient; Leaf litter quality; Shredder detritivores; Stream ecosystems","abundance; detritivory; freshwater ecosystem; global change; global warming; guild; leaf litter; species diversity; stream; trophic structure; water temperature; animal; article; biodiversity; demography; feeding behavior; food chain; invertebrate; physiology; Animals; Biodiversity; Demography; Feeding Behavior; Food Chain; Invertebrates",,,,,,"Arita, H.T., Vazquez-Dominguez, E., The tropics: Cradle, museum or casino? A dynamic null model for latitudinal gradients of species diversity (2008) Ecology Letters, 11 (7), pp. 653-663. , DOI 10.1111/j.1461-0248.2008.01197.x; Boyero, L., A global experiment suggests climate warming will not accelerate litter decomposition in streams but might reduce carbon sequestration (2011) Ecology Letters, 4, pp. 289-294; Boyero, L., Ramírez, A., Dudgeon, D., Pearson, R.G., Are tropical streams really different? (2009) Journal of the North American Benthological Society, 28, pp. 397-403; Camacho, R., Boyero, L., Cornejo, A., Ibáñez, A., Pearson, R.G., Local variation in shredder distribution can explain their oversight in tropical streams (2009) Biotropica, 41, pp. 625-632; Cheshire, K., Boyero, L., Pearson, R.G., Food webs in tropical Australian streams: Shredders are not scarce (2005) Freshwater Biology, 50 (5), pp. 748-769. , D